1
00:00:24,275 --> 00:00:26,266
Here we go.

2
00:00:26,344 --> 00:00:31,179
- Could you take this for me? Thanks a lot.
- <i>Sure.</i>

3
00:00:31,249 --> 00:00:33,183
Appreciate it.

4
00:00:33,251 --> 00:00:37,085
Giddap! Let's go!
Cracker, come on!

5
00:00:38,856 --> 00:00:40,847
Hyah!

6
00:00:48,333 --> 00:00:51,325
<i>[Children Chattering, Laughing]</i>

7
00:00:53,504 --> 00:00:56,439
[Bell Ringing]

8
00:00:56,507 --> 00:00:59,032
- Come on, children. Recess is over.
- Here we go.

9
00:00:59,110 --> 00:01:02,011
Maddie, Jacob, inside.

10
00:01:02,080 --> 00:01:05,072
[Chattering, Laughing Continue]

11
00:01:06,584 --> 00:01:08,518
[Sobbing]

12
00:01:08,586 --> 00:01:10,520
Emily, what happened?

13
00:01:10,588 --> 00:01:12,886
I fell off the swing
and broke my arm.

14
00:01:12,957 --> 00:01:16,154
- I fell off swings a lot when I was little.
- Did you hurt your arm?

15
00:01:16,227 --> 00:01:19,060
- My arm, my leg, my fingers.
- Twice.

16
00:01:19,130 --> 00:01:21,064
- My nose.
- [Laughs]

17
00:01:21,132 --> 00:01:23,123
- You fell a lot.
- She sure did.

18
00:01:23,201 --> 00:01:25,328
Can you wiggle your fingers?

19
00:01:27,638 --> 00:01:30,903
<i>Know what? You didn't break your arm.</i>
<i>Just bruised it a little.</i>

20
00:01:30,975 --> 00:01:33,239
- Can I go back to school?
- Sure can.

21
00:01:33,311 --> 00:01:35,302
Just wash that up.
Okay?

22
00:01:36,814 --> 00:01:38,748
You are a natural born caretaker, Lindy.

23
00:01:38,816 --> 00:01:41,307
'Cause I can tell a bruise
from a broken bone?

24
00:01:41,386 --> 00:01:44,981
Because you can make people feel better
when they're hurt and scared.

25
00:01:45,056 --> 00:01:46,887
Just like you, Mama.

26
00:01:54,999 --> 00:01:58,230
- Lindy, what brings you into town?
- Came to get my newspapers.

27
00:01:58,302 --> 00:02:01,169
And I thought I'd ask my best fella
to take me to lunch at the hotel.

28
00:02:01,239 --> 00:02:05,232
One of these days somebody else is gonna be
your best fella and I'm gonna get jealous.

29
00:02:05,309 --> 00:02:09,075
There may be another fella in my life someday,
but you'll always be the best papa.

30
00:02:09,147 --> 00:02:12,207
That's worth the best meal
the hotel has to offer.

31
00:02:12,283 --> 00:02:17,118
How'd you get to be so clever
to wrap me around your little finger?

32
00:02:17,188 --> 00:02:20,282
- I hear Dr. Jackson is looking for a new assistant.
- You mean it?

33
00:02:20,358 --> 00:02:24,089
- Absolutely.
- I'd better get there before
somebody else gets the job!

34
00:02:24,162 --> 00:02:26,858
- What about lunch?
- Another time, Papa.

35
00:02:29,534 --> 00:02:32,059
So much for bein' her best fella.

36
00:02:42,680 --> 00:02:45,581
[Sewing Machine Whirring]

37
00:02:50,988 --> 00:02:53,286
- Hey.
- [Gasps] Clark!

38
00:02:53,357 --> 00:02:55,587
You startled me.

39
00:02:55,660 --> 00:02:58,128
- What are these for?
- Nothing in particular.

40
00:02:58,196 --> 00:03:01,290
Maybe I just wanted to give
my beautiful wife some flowers.

41
00:03:01,365 --> 00:03:04,300
Mr. Davis, you do turn my head.

42
00:03:04,368 --> 00:03:06,165
Enough to steal a kiss?

43
00:03:06,237 --> 00:03:08,171
You don't have to steal it.

44
00:03:08,239 --> 00:03:11,436
- Grandma?
- Grandpa!

45
00:03:11,509 --> 00:03:13,568
Did you get all the eggs?

46
00:03:13,644 --> 00:03:17,136
- <i>The reds lay in the barn. Did you check there?</i>
- No.

47
00:03:17,215 --> 00:03:19,683
Stop lollygagging around.
Come on. Get to it.

48
00:03:19,750 --> 00:03:21,741
Yes, sir.

49
00:03:22,487 --> 00:03:24,182
[Laughing]
Clark.

50
00:03:26,123 --> 00:03:28,114
Morning.

51
00:03:36,667 --> 00:03:38,862
Doc Jackson, I'm here
for the assistant position.

52
00:03:38,936 --> 00:03:42,702
Oh, you just hold on there, Belinda.
I can't hire you.

53
00:03:42,773 --> 00:03:44,764
But I know sutures
and basic first aid.

54
00:03:44,842 --> 00:03:47,834
I even learned a new wrapping technique
for sprains that Dr. Usla recommends.

55
00:03:47,912 --> 00:03:49,675
Where'd you learn that?

56
00:03:49,747 --> 00:03:52,511
I read his book. I've read a lot of
medical books and newspaper articles.

57
00:03:52,583 --> 00:03:56,610
- Everything I get my hands on.
- Reading a few books doesn't make you qualified.

58
00:03:56,687 --> 00:03:58,621
<i>Without proper medical training...</i>

59
00:03:58,689 --> 00:04:01,055
all that book knowledge is useless.

60
00:04:01,125 --> 00:04:04,219
But I can learn. I know more
than anyone in Anderson Corner.

61
00:04:04,295 --> 00:04:06,229
Well, I don't doubt it.

62
00:04:06,297 --> 00:04:10,358
<i>But what I need is someone</i>
<i>with solid patient experience.</i>

63
00:04:10,434 --> 00:04:14,370
This is all I've ever wanted to do with my life.
I could learn so much from you, Doc.

64
00:04:14,438 --> 00:04:17,236
Women aren't supposed to be doctors.
What about marriage?

65
00:04:17,308 --> 00:04:19,299
- I'm not gettin' married.
- Ever?

66
00:04:19,377 --> 00:04:23,711
- Well, Doc, I mean-
- Women are meant to marry and have children.

67
00:04:23,781 --> 00:04:27,217
Which is exactly what you'll do
when the right man comes along.

68
00:04:27,285 --> 00:04:31,153
Trust me, marriage and
a career in medicine will never work.

69
00:04:31,222 --> 00:04:33,156
I'm not giving up.

70
00:04:33,224 --> 00:04:37,160
Dr. Elizabeth Blackwell applied to 29 schools
before she got accepted into Geneva College.

71
00:04:37,228 --> 00:04:40,356
Elizabeth Blackwell
is the exception, not the rule.

72
00:04:40,431 --> 00:04:45,232
Now, Geneva College may accept
your application, but I won't. Good day.

73
00:04:45,303 --> 00:04:47,294
Come on.

74
00:04:55,479 --> 00:04:57,447
Whoa.

75
00:05:05,122 --> 00:05:08,057
- Hey.
- Hey, Clark, what can I do for ya?

76
00:05:08,125 --> 00:05:11,253
I just came into town to pick up
some supplies from the general store.

77
00:05:11,329 --> 00:05:16,266
Thought I would stop by to see if the five of you
would like to come out to dinner tonight.

78
00:05:16,334 --> 00:05:19,895
Sounds good. I'm always happy
to eat at your house instead of mine.

79
00:05:19,971 --> 00:05:23,134
- Oh, really?
- Not that Missie's cooking isn't good.

80
00:05:23,207 --> 00:05:25,402
- It's interesting.
- It's all right, Zach.

81
00:05:25,476 --> 00:05:29,572
I love my daughter dearly, but I have to admit
she does not take after her mama...

82
00:05:29,647 --> 00:05:31,911
<i>when it comes to cooking.</i>

83
00:05:33,017 --> 00:05:34,609
Excuse me, Sheriff.

84
00:05:34,685 --> 00:05:38,052
- What can I do for you?
- I'm Drew Simpson.

85
00:05:38,122 --> 00:05:41,114
- My uncle was Hank Simpson.
- Hank was a fine man. My condolences.

86
00:05:41,192 --> 00:05:45,060
- Well, thank you, Mr. -
- Davis. Clark Davis.

87
00:05:45,129 --> 00:05:48,656
Our place is next to Hank's.
He was a good neighbor.

88
00:05:48,733 --> 00:05:52,829
Unfortunately I didn't have the opportunity
to meet Uncle Hank, living so far away and all.

89
00:05:52,903 --> 00:05:55,064
- Where you from?
- New York City.

90
00:05:55,139 --> 00:05:57,767
New York City. I'll bet that's
a sight different than our little town.

91
00:05:57,842 --> 00:06:00,675
Oh, yes.
Well, I mean, it's much bigger.

92
00:06:00,745 --> 00:06:03,612
A little bit more cultured
and sophisticated.

93
00:06:03,681 --> 00:06:07,708
<i>This place is clearly rather rustic.</i>

94
00:06:07,785 --> 00:06:09,980
- Rustic.
- [Clears Throat]

95
00:06:10,054 --> 00:06:11,988
Anyway,
the stage driver suggested...

96
00:06:12,056 --> 00:06:14,650
I ask you for directions to my uncle's place.

97
00:06:14,725 --> 00:06:18,252
I can do better than that. Got my buckboard
outside. I'll take you out there myself.

98
00:06:18,329 --> 00:06:20,297
That's awful kind of you, Mr. Davis.

99
00:06:20,364 --> 00:06:22,161
- Sheriff.
- Good day.

100
00:06:24,035 --> 00:06:26,026
- Get up, boys.
- [Horse Whinnies]

101
00:06:37,348 --> 00:06:39,213
Whoa.

102
00:06:39,283 --> 00:06:41,217
Hold these.

103
00:06:45,056 --> 00:06:48,321
Squatters settled in
after your uncle passed.

104
00:06:48,392 --> 00:06:51,793
I'm afraid they didn't
take care of your place properly.

105
00:06:51,862 --> 00:06:54,387
I'd hoped it would be
in good enough shape to sell right away.

106
00:06:54,465 --> 00:06:57,696
- You're not staying.
- Certainly not.

107
00:07:08,612 --> 00:07:11,979
Gonna take a sight of work
to make it presentable.

108
00:07:12,049 --> 00:07:15,985
Pack rats gonna settle into those walls
if you don't get those holes patched up.

109
00:07:16,053 --> 00:07:19,580
- Do you know anyone I could hire to do that?
- You don't want to yourself?

110
00:07:19,657 --> 00:07:21,591
I just graduated from law school.

111
00:07:21,659 --> 00:07:24,594
I know all about writs and torts
and the right of habeas corpus...

112
00:07:24,662 --> 00:07:27,153
but nothing about working on a farm.

113
00:07:27,231 --> 00:07:29,426
- I'd be happy to help you.
- Would you? Thank you.

114
00:07:29,500 --> 00:07:32,867
- I'll pay you, of course.
- That's mighty generous, but no thanks.

115
00:07:32,937 --> 00:07:34,905
I can't let you work for nothing.

116
00:07:34,972 --> 00:07:38,567
You'd be allowing me to
repay a debt to a good friend.

117
00:07:38,642 --> 00:07:41,202
- Then I accept.
- Good.

118
00:07:43,247 --> 00:07:45,181
- <i>[Missie] Please sit down.</i>
- <i>Thank you.</i>

119
00:07:45,249 --> 00:07:48,082
<i>It's great that you could come in today.</i>
<i>I really appreciate it.</i>

120
00:07:48,152 --> 00:07:50,086
- <i>It's no problem.</i>
- <i>Nice to see you.</i>

121
00:07:50,154 --> 00:07:53,089
<i>We haven't had a chance to</i>
<i>talk since you moved here, Mrs. Kent.</i>

122
00:07:53,157 --> 00:07:55,352
Please call me Sadie.

123
00:07:55,426 --> 00:07:57,360
Caleb is a bright boy.

124
00:07:57,428 --> 00:08:01,421
But he's very behind for his age,
especially in reading and writing.

125
00:08:01,499 --> 00:08:04,935
He isn't doing his homework, and he said
that you and his father won't help him with it.

126
00:08:05,002 --> 00:08:07,937
I'm afraid my husband Charles
don't hold much with schoolwork.

127
00:08:08,005 --> 00:08:10,565
I'm sure you understand
the importance of a good education.

128
00:08:10,641 --> 00:08:13,576
I know how bad it feels
when you don't have one.

129
00:08:13,644 --> 00:08:15,578
I only got through
the second grade...

130
00:08:15,646 --> 00:08:18,581
before I had to take care
of the younger kids.

131
00:08:19,950 --> 00:08:22,817
The fact is, I can only read
a few words in this paper.

132
00:08:22,887 --> 00:08:27,790
So it's not that you won't help him,
it's just that you can't.

133
00:08:27,858 --> 00:08:29,951
- What about your husband?
- He can't read at all.

134
00:08:30,027 --> 00:08:32,461
I will spend some
extra time with Caleb.

135
00:08:32,530 --> 00:08:37,229
But with 14 students of different ages
and grades, it's going to be difficult.

136
00:08:37,301 --> 00:08:41,135
Thank you, Mrs. Tyler.
I appreciate anything you can do for him.

137
00:08:41,205 --> 00:08:43,002
l-

138
00:08:43,073 --> 00:08:46,907
You know, Sadie, I could teach you how to read,
and then you could help Caleb to learn.

139
00:08:46,977 --> 00:08:49,741
I-I have to go, Mrs. Tyler.

140
00:08:54,752 --> 00:08:56,686
<i>[Missie]</i>
<i>I should have figured it out.</i>

141
00:08:56,754 --> 00:08:59,689
The Kents have kept to themselves
since they moved into town.

142
00:08:59,757 --> 00:09:01,622
You couldn't have known, Mama.

143
00:09:01,692 --> 00:09:04,627
The signs were all there.
I just missed them.

144
00:09:04,695 --> 00:09:06,629
Hey, Mom. Hey, Sis.
What's for dinner?

145
00:09:06,697 --> 00:09:10,599
Brunswick stew. And it's almost ready,
so you boys go and wash up for supper.

146
00:09:11,735 --> 00:09:14,499
<i>[Groans]</i>

147
00:09:16,340 --> 00:09:19,173
Can we go to Grandma
and Grandpa's for dinner?

148
00:09:19,243 --> 00:09:22,371
<i>Not tonight.</i>
<i>Go do what your mama said.</i>

149
00:09:23,514 --> 00:09:25,448
What does Charles Kent do?

150
00:09:25,516 --> 00:09:29,452
George has hired him part-time at
the general store. He does other odd jobs.

151
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:31,647
Mostly he wants to
get a farm for himself.

152
00:09:31,722 --> 00:09:34,350
- How did you get all that out of him?
- I asked him.

153
00:09:34,425 --> 00:09:36,325
He doesn't seem very talkative to me.

154
00:09:36,393 --> 00:09:38,827
Well, generally, when the sheriff
asks questions people give answers.

155
00:09:38,896 --> 00:09:40,830
If Mrs. Kent would learn to read...

156
00:09:40,898 --> 00:09:43,833
a whole new world would open up for her,
just like it did for me, Mama.

157
00:09:43,901 --> 00:09:45,664
She'd become a different person.

158
00:09:45,736 --> 00:09:47,465
Maybe that's what
her husband is afraid of.

159
00:09:47,538 --> 00:09:50,200
What kind of woman allows her husband
to dictate to her that way?

160
00:09:50,274 --> 00:09:54,176
I wouldn't know, Lindy.
I haven't had any experience with that kind.

161
00:09:54,245 --> 00:09:56,179
And you never will, Zachary Tyler.

162
00:09:56,247 --> 00:09:58,238
- Oh.
- [Laughs]

163
00:10:02,853 --> 00:10:04,821
<i>Miss! Hello, Miss!</i>

164
00:10:04,889 --> 00:10:07,483
- Is there a doctor in town?
- Yes. Are you hurt?

165
00:10:07,558 --> 00:10:11,722
No, not me. My employer, Mrs. Stafford-Smith,
has grown gravely ill.

166
00:10:11,795 --> 00:10:15,094
<i>We were on the stagecoach passing through</i>
<i>when Mrs. Stafford-Smith became ill.</i>

167
00:10:15,165 --> 00:10:18,396
- <i>I fear for her life.</i>
- <i>I didn't think she'd make it, Miss.</i>

168
00:10:18,469 --> 00:10:21,199
- How long has she been like this?
- An hour or so, Miss.

169
00:10:24,842 --> 00:10:27,106
Whoa. Whoa.

170
00:10:27,177 --> 00:10:29,805
Doc, I got a patient for you.

171
00:10:35,185 --> 00:10:38,120
All right, bring her
over here on the table.

172
00:10:38,188 --> 00:10:40,179
<i>Put her right here.</i>

173
00:10:41,625 --> 00:10:44,992
Put her right-That's it.
All right. All right.

174
00:10:45,062 --> 00:10:46,996
Watch her head.

175
00:10:47,064 --> 00:10:48,998
Watch her head.
All right.

176
00:10:49,066 --> 00:10:51,000
Okay.

177
00:10:51,068 --> 00:10:55,471
Her breathing is fine. Pulse is steady.
Her skin's clammy to the touch, Doc.

178
00:10:55,539 --> 00:10:57,404
<i>Mrs. Stafford-Smith</i>
<i>began slurring her words.</i>

179
00:10:57,474 --> 00:10:59,305
Her sentences didn't make sense.
Then she collapsed.

180
00:10:59,376 --> 00:11:01,936
- She been drinking?
- Of course not!

181
00:11:02,012 --> 00:11:06,244
<i>Mrs. Stafford-Smith has</i>
<i>an occasional glass of sherry, but she is a lady!</i>

182
00:11:06,317 --> 00:11:09,912
- How long y'all been traveling?
- We left Beacon Hill nearly two weeks ago.

183
00:11:09,987 --> 00:11:12,820
- What's she doing out here?
- Visiting friends in Denver.

184
00:11:12,890 --> 00:11:15,825
- The Montgomerys. A very prominent family.
- Do you think she had a stroke?

185
00:11:15,893 --> 00:11:19,260
- Why would you say that?
- I read about the symptoms in <i>Gray's Anatomy.</i>

186
00:11:19,330 --> 00:11:23,426
- Can you help her, Doctor?
- Unfortunately, I have another patient.

187
00:11:23,500 --> 00:11:25,764
Possibly a breach birth.

188
00:11:25,836 --> 00:11:27,770
But you can't leave
Mrs. Stafford-Smith!

189
00:11:27,838 --> 00:11:30,602
<i>Well, there's nothing I can do for her</i>
<i>until she comes to.</i>

190
00:11:30,674 --> 00:11:32,608
And she seems fairly stable.

191
00:11:32,676 --> 00:11:35,008
There's only one of me.

192
00:11:35,079 --> 00:11:39,516
<i>My other patient's situation is urgent,</i>
<i>so just watch out for her until I get back.</i>

193
00:11:39,583 --> 00:11:43,110
- I'll stay, Doc.
- Well, I don't have much choice, do I?

194
00:11:43,187 --> 00:11:46,156
All right, just make sure
she's comfortable...

195
00:11:46,223 --> 00:11:48,157
and keep a close eye on her.

196
00:11:48,225 --> 00:11:51,683
I'll get back as soon as I can.

197
00:12:06,410 --> 00:12:08,378
Mrs. Tyler?

198
00:12:08,445 --> 00:12:12,142
Hi, Sadie.
I just wanted to talk to you about-

199
00:12:13,217 --> 00:12:15,208
- My boy in trouble at school?
- Oh, no.

200
00:12:15,285 --> 00:12:17,048
Nothing like that.

201
00:12:17,121 --> 00:12:20,056
I stopped to bring some books for Mrs. Kent
I thought she might be interested in.

202
00:12:20,124 --> 00:12:21,819
- You ask her for books?
- No.

203
00:12:21,892 --> 00:12:24,725
No, she didn't.
I-I thought that-

204
00:12:24,795 --> 00:12:27,730
Well, you thought wrong.
She got no use for books here.

205
00:12:27,798 --> 00:12:30,494
<i>Now if you got a job you're offering,</i>
<i>that's a different story.</i>

206
00:12:30,567 --> 00:12:32,899
No, I'm afraid not.

207
00:12:43,414 --> 00:12:45,541
Dr. Jackson, she's awake!

208
00:12:46,583 --> 00:12:48,483
H-Heaven's day-

209
00:12:48,552 --> 00:12:51,043
- Get up. Get up.
- <i>[Groaning]</i>

210
00:12:51,121 --> 00:12:55,057
<i>Mrs. Stafford-Smith,</i>
<i>my name is Dr. Jackson...</i>

211
00:12:55,125 --> 00:12:58,060
and I believe you've had a stroke.

212
00:12:58,128 --> 00:13:02,428
My photos- coach- bags-

213
00:13:02,499 --> 00:13:06,060
Calm down. Calm down.
This is not good for you, ma'am.

214
00:13:06,136 --> 00:13:09,435
Have-All that's left-

215
00:13:09,506 --> 00:13:11,337
I have your bag right here.

216
00:13:11,408 --> 00:13:14,070
All your things are inside.

217
00:13:14,144 --> 00:13:17,136
[Sighs]

218
00:13:18,315 --> 00:13:20,408
Her speech
has obviously been impaired.

219
00:13:20,484 --> 00:13:23,578
Well, I don't think it's as bad
as it could have been.

220
00:13:23,654 --> 00:13:27,090
<i>Hopefully the slurring will</i>
<i>diminish pretty quickly...</i>

221
00:13:27,157 --> 00:13:29,591
<i>and she'll regain coherent speech.</i>

222
00:13:29,660 --> 00:13:32,094
There's some paralysis
on her right side...

223
00:13:32,162 --> 00:13:34,096
but her left side seems unaffected.

224
00:13:34,164 --> 00:13:37,531
As soon as she's well enough,
I could help her do some movement therapy.

225
00:13:37,601 --> 00:13:40,536
I read they're having
good results with that.

226
00:13:40,604 --> 00:13:43,038
Well, she will need
someone with her constantly...

227
00:13:43,107 --> 00:13:45,473
till we get a better grasp
of her physical limitations.

228
00:13:45,542 --> 00:13:47,601
I won't leave her side, Doctor.

229
00:13:47,678 --> 00:13:52,445
It should be someone with at least
rudimentary medical knowledge.

230
00:13:52,516 --> 00:13:54,450
[Sighs]
Belinda-

231
00:13:54,518 --> 00:13:56,452
I can do it!

232
00:13:56,520 --> 00:13:59,921
I don't want you to misinterpret this
as a permanent job offer, young lady.

233
00:13:59,990 --> 00:14:03,619
- I haven't changed my mind
about women in medicine.
- So I'd be like your assistant?

234
00:14:03,694 --> 00:14:05,628
Not exactly.

235
00:14:05,696 --> 00:14:07,630
You will help Mrs. Stafford-Smith...

236
00:14:07,698 --> 00:14:09,632
with her movement therapy.

237
00:14:09,700 --> 00:14:12,828
- That is all.
- I accept.

238
00:14:29,720 --> 00:14:32,655
<i>Well, good morning.</i>

239
00:14:32,723 --> 00:14:34,884
Something I can do for you, son?

240
00:14:34,958 --> 00:14:38,485
Uh, well, yes, I've got this problem.

241
00:14:38,562 --> 00:14:42,521
- Mm-hmm.
- A carbuncle that is driving me crazy.

242
00:14:42,599 --> 00:14:46,194
And you see,
the area that's affected...

243
00:14:46,270 --> 00:14:49,398
has been getting a good deal of sitting time,
if you know what I mean.

244
00:14:49,473 --> 00:14:53,136
Oh. You're trying to tell me
you've got a boil on your backside.

245
00:14:53,210 --> 00:14:58,204
<i>Well, bend over the table,</i>
<i>drop your drawers and we'll have a look.</i>

246
00:15:05,856 --> 00:15:11,294
Oh! That is a mean-looking carbuncle
you got there, all right.

247
00:15:11,361 --> 00:15:15,195
Uh, would you bring me
some of that rider's liniment.

248
00:15:15,265 --> 00:15:18,029
It's on the top shelf in there.

249
00:15:18,101 --> 00:15:20,037
Would you stop rubbing!

250
00:15:20,171 --> 00:15:24,073
- I can't help it.
- Well, the more you scratch it, the itchier it gets.

251
00:15:24,141 --> 00:15:26,109
Here you go, Doc.

252
00:15:26,177 --> 00:15:28,645
Oh! Hey, now. Whoa!

253
00:15:28,712 --> 00:15:31,146
- Wait. Never mind.
- Well-

254
00:15:31,215 --> 00:15:34,184
- W-What about your carbuncle?
- What carbuncle?

255
00:15:34,251 --> 00:15:37,846
<i>Well, at least take the liniment.</i>
<i>Belinda!</i>

256
00:15:42,026 --> 00:15:44,017
Doctor.

257
00:15:44,094 --> 00:15:45,959
[Giggling]

258
00:15:46,030 --> 00:15:49,261
You see, that's another reason
I can't hire a woman.

259
00:15:49,333 --> 00:15:53,531
How am I going to make my money
with you scaring away my patients?

260
00:15:59,577 --> 00:16:01,442
Well, what do you think?

261
00:16:01,512 --> 00:16:03,446
Let me get this straight.

262
00:16:03,514 --> 00:16:06,449
You want to hire Sadie
to help you at school...

263
00:16:06,517 --> 00:16:09,042
so you can teach her to read
without her husband knowing?

264
00:16:09,119 --> 00:16:12,520
- It's an ingenious plan, if you ask me.
- What will you have her do?

265
00:16:12,590 --> 00:16:16,686
Whatever needs to be done. Sweep the floors,
clean blackboards, keep the wood stove burning.

266
00:16:16,760 --> 00:16:20,321
Simple things that allow her to
learn along with the children.

267
00:16:20,397 --> 00:16:23,662
Don't you think the way you're
going about this is just a little sneaky?

268
00:16:23,734 --> 00:16:26,669
I think the Lord
will forgive my methods...

269
00:16:26,737 --> 00:16:30,537
if I can offer this poor woman
a path out of the darkness of ignorance.

270
00:16:36,714 --> 00:16:39,740
<i>Lindy, how long is Doc gonna</i>
<i>let you stay on at the clinic?</i>

271
00:16:39,817 --> 00:16:42,251
As long as Mrs. Stafford-Smith
needs me.

272
00:16:42,319 --> 00:16:45,254
After that Doc says I get the boot.

273
00:16:45,322 --> 00:16:49,656
You will prove yourself so indispensable
that he will never want to let you go.

274
00:16:49,727 --> 00:16:51,718
That's the idea.

275
00:16:54,064 --> 00:16:57,033
Grandma, there's one too many
plates for the table.

276
00:16:57,101 --> 00:17:00,036
We have a guest
joining us for supper.

277
00:17:00,104 --> 00:17:02,732
Come on in, young man.
Let me introduce you.

278
00:17:02,806 --> 00:17:04,740
This is my wife Marty.

279
00:17:04,808 --> 00:17:06,241
- Hi.
- Hi.

280
00:17:06,310 --> 00:17:08,608
- My daughter Missie.
- How do you do?

281
00:17:08,679 --> 00:17:12,547
And this is my granddaughter Belinda.
Lindy, this is Mr. Drew Simpson.

282
00:17:12,616 --> 00:17:15,779
<i>He inherited Hank's place, and he's</i>
<i>come all the way from New York City.</i>

283
00:17:15,853 --> 00:17:18,583
It's a pleasure to meet you,
Mr. Simpson.

284
00:17:18,656 --> 00:17:21,250
I trust your journey here hasn't left you
suffering any adverse affects.

285
00:17:21,325 --> 00:17:24,055
Nothing worth speaking of.

286
00:17:24,128 --> 00:17:28,030
- We're all very interested
in hearing about your journey.
- I know I am.

287
00:17:28,098 --> 00:17:30,362
- Yeah.
- We're having a simple dinner.

288
00:17:30,434 --> 00:17:32,800
Fried chicken.
I hope you like it.

289
00:17:32,870 --> 00:17:35,805
Lord, we thank you for the food
that's in front of us...

290
00:17:35,873 --> 00:17:37,807
the family that surrounds us...

291
00:17:37,875 --> 00:17:40,810
and the new friend
that's joined us at our table.

292
00:17:40,878 --> 00:17:42,709
- Amen.
- Amen.

293
00:17:42,780 --> 00:17:45,374
Ah-ah-ah!
Jacob, honey. Guests first.

294
00:17:45,449 --> 00:17:47,383
Would you like a biscuit,
Mr. Simpson?

295
00:17:47,451 --> 00:17:51,717
- Thank you.
- I'm sorry about your uncle.
He was a wonderful man.

296
00:17:51,789 --> 00:17:55,054
Belinda spent quite a bit of time with him
in his last few weeks.

297
00:17:55,125 --> 00:17:58,652
- She nursed him right to the very end.
- That was very kind of you.

298
00:17:58,729 --> 00:18:00,663
Well, Lindy's a natural caretaker.

299
00:18:00,731 --> 00:18:03,598
In fact, she's working
in town with Doc Jackson.

300
00:18:03,667 --> 00:18:06,158
- I hope to be a doctor someday.
- Oh.

301
00:18:06,236 --> 00:18:08,431
That's rather unusual, isn't it?

302
00:18:08,505 --> 00:18:10,700
- Pardon me?
- A woman doctor.

303
00:18:10,774 --> 00:18:13,766
- It doesn't seem quite appropriate.
- Appropriate?

304
00:18:13,844 --> 00:18:18,781
Why would a lady want to subject herself to such
a mentally and physically taxing line of work?

305
00:18:18,849 --> 00:18:20,749
Oh, boy.

306
00:18:20,818 --> 00:18:23,446
I would think being from New York City you
would have a more enlightened view of women.

307
00:18:23,520 --> 00:18:26,455
And by enlightened I assume you mean
a view that agrees with yours.

308
00:18:26,523 --> 00:18:29,617
<i>Ladies are as capable</i>
<i>of practicing medicine as men are.</i>

309
00:18:29,693 --> 00:18:32,093
<i>I could recommend several</i>
<i>newspaper articles for you to read.</i>

310
00:18:32,162 --> 00:18:34,289
That is, if you're open
to being educated.

311
00:18:34,365 --> 00:18:37,300
I think you'll find the majority of men
uncomfortable...

312
00:18:37,368 --> 00:18:40,132
being tended to
by someone of the weaker sex.

313
00:18:40,204 --> 00:18:44,664
<i>That's true. Some men might be so intimidated</i>
<i>that they run away in embarrassment.</i>

314
00:18:44,742 --> 00:18:47,540
I'm just saying that,
like most men...

315
00:18:47,611 --> 00:18:49,943
when I marry
I'll need my wife at home.

316
00:18:50,014 --> 00:18:52,949
She'll have enough to do
just taking care of me and our children.

317
00:18:53,017 --> 00:18:55,042
- I'm sure she will.
- More potatoes, anyone?

318
00:18:55,119 --> 00:18:57,280
- Yes.
- <i>Please!</i>

319
00:19:04,361 --> 00:19:07,262
You're awake. Good.

320
00:19:07,331 --> 00:19:09,526
How are you feeling,
Mrs. Stafford-Smith?

321
00:19:09,600 --> 00:19:11,397
Tired.

322
00:19:15,739 --> 00:19:17,673
Here.

323
00:19:17,741 --> 00:19:21,575
No!
Don't need help.

324
00:19:21,645 --> 00:19:25,206
- Your speech is better today.
- But not my arm.

325
00:19:25,282 --> 00:19:29,218
With movement therapy it's possible
to regain the use of your arm. Like this.

326
00:19:29,286 --> 00:19:31,220
Don't touch me.

327
00:19:31,288 --> 00:19:33,722
<i>[Footsteps]</i>

328
00:19:33,791 --> 00:19:37,591
You're awake, madam.
This is wonderful!

329
00:19:39,263 --> 00:19:42,858
- Don't fuss over me, Windsor.
- Sorry, madam.

330
00:19:42,933 --> 00:19:45,868
- We should let her get some rest.
- Of course, Miss.

331
00:19:45,936 --> 00:19:49,667
I'll be in the next room, Madam.
I won't leave you.

332
00:19:49,740 --> 00:19:52,174
I know you won't, Windsor.

333
00:19:59,516 --> 00:20:01,450
<i>I'd be at a great disadvantage...</i>

334
00:20:01,518 --> 00:20:05,045
if you hadn't been available
to help me fix up the place, Mr. Davis.

335
00:20:05,122 --> 00:20:08,057
I'd never have got it
good enough to sell.

336
00:20:08,125 --> 00:20:10,389
Glad to do it.

337
00:20:10,461 --> 00:20:14,022
- <i>You be careful now you don't</i>
<i>catch yourself on a rusty-</i>
- Ow!

338
00:20:14,098 --> 00:20:16,032
Wire. Hold on.

339
00:20:16,100 --> 00:20:20,628
- Let me take a look at it. Let me see it.
- Naw, it's nothing.

340
00:20:22,039 --> 00:20:24,371
Yeah, that puncture wound is deep.

341
00:20:24,441 --> 00:20:28,070
I'll tell you, one thing you don't
mess around with is rusty wire.

342
00:20:28,145 --> 00:20:30,238
You'll get a nasty infection.

343
00:20:30,314 --> 00:20:32,805
I want you to go into town,
see the doc.

344
00:20:32,883 --> 00:20:36,876
- I'm fine, really.
- Go on now. You don't mess with rust in a cut.

345
00:20:36,954 --> 00:20:38,888
- I'll finish up here.
- Yes, sir.

346
00:20:38,956 --> 00:20:40,947
All right.

347
00:20:42,226 --> 00:20:44,217
Whoa.

348
00:20:51,869 --> 00:20:53,860
<i>[Clicking Tongue]</i>

349
00:21:00,477 --> 00:21:02,411
[Exhales]

350
00:21:05,782 --> 00:21:07,841
Afternoon, Mr. Simpson.

351
00:21:07,918 --> 00:21:12,082
Good afternoon, Miss Tyler.
I came to see Doctor Jackson about my hand.

352
00:21:12,156 --> 00:21:15,853
He's out checking on patients.
Why? What's wrong?

353
00:21:15,926 --> 00:21:17,860
A little run-in with a rusty wire.

354
00:21:17,928 --> 00:21:20,624
- When do you expect the doc to return?
- Not for hours.

355
00:21:22,099 --> 00:21:24,033
Rusty wire?

356
00:21:24,101 --> 00:21:26,501
Tetanus can take hold pretty quick.

357
00:21:26,570 --> 00:21:29,767
- Might end up losing the hand.
- I think you're exaggerating.

358
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:32,866
I understand that you're uncomfortable
being tended to by the weaker sex...

359
00:21:32,943 --> 00:21:35,878
but unless we clean that wound immediately
it might be too late.

360
00:21:35,946 --> 00:21:37,880
Lockjaw could set in by tonight.

361
00:21:37,948 --> 00:21:41,384
Although that may
not be the worst thing.

362
00:21:41,451 --> 00:21:43,214
All right.

363
00:21:43,287 --> 00:21:46,222
How much humble pie do I have to eat
to persuade you to help me?

364
00:21:46,290 --> 00:21:51,387
Enough to make me believe you sincerely regret
saying I have no business becoming a doctor.

365
00:21:51,461 --> 00:21:53,861
[Sighs]
I most sincerely regret it.

366
00:21:53,931 --> 00:21:55,865
Come inside.

367
00:21:59,870 --> 00:22:02,737
My grandpa tells me
you went to Columbia University.

368
00:22:02,806 --> 00:22:05,741
You didn't mention that
the other day at dinner.

369
00:22:05,809 --> 00:22:07,743
I guess I could have worked that in...

370
00:22:07,811 --> 00:22:10,746
when you offered to recommend articles
to help enlighten me.

371
00:22:10,814 --> 00:22:12,748
That would have been a good time.

372
00:22:12,816 --> 00:22:15,683
You're so fortunate to have
the opportunity to study at Columbia.

373
00:22:15,752 --> 00:22:19,518
- I suppose that's true.
- I can't be a doctor without the proper education.

374
00:22:19,590 --> 00:22:23,185
Most hospitals won't even consider me
for a nursing position.

375
00:22:23,260 --> 00:22:26,229
The proper education requires
a great deal of money.

376
00:22:26,296 --> 00:22:28,355
I've been saving for a long time.

377
00:22:28,432 --> 00:22:31,094
- [Hisses]
- I'm sorry if it stings.

378
00:22:31,168 --> 00:22:33,432
No, no, it's all right.

379
00:22:33,503 --> 00:22:35,664
Actually, you've been very gentle.

380
00:22:39,276 --> 00:22:41,267
There.
You're all set.

381
00:22:42,546 --> 00:22:44,980
Remember to keep the wound cleaned.

382
00:22:45,048 --> 00:22:49,951
At the risk of bringing up an old argument,
you're a bright and beautiful young woman-

383
00:22:50,020 --> 00:22:52,045
- Beautiful?
- Yes.

384
00:22:52,122 --> 00:22:54,022
<i>[Clears Throat]</i>

385
00:22:54,091 --> 00:22:56,116
Anyway, you'll surely
be married before long.

386
00:22:56,193 --> 00:23:00,061
Why would you want to waste your time
preparing for a career that you'll have to leave?

387
00:23:00,130 --> 00:23:03,998
Why does every man assume
that I'm on a hunt for a husband?

388
00:23:04,067 --> 00:23:07,127
Isn't that the goal?
Find a mate, settle down, have children?

389
00:23:07,204 --> 00:23:10,605
As a lawyer, everything
is black or white to you, isn't it?

390
00:23:10,674 --> 00:23:13,438
Well, that's-
that's rather simplistic.

391
00:23:13,510 --> 00:23:17,810
<i>But there is a clear-cut sense of right and wrong</i>
<i>in the law that I've come to appreciate.</i>

392
00:23:17,881 --> 00:23:19,815
That's why we're different.

393
00:23:19,883 --> 00:23:21,817
I see all of God's colors.

394
00:23:21,885 --> 00:23:25,252
And somewhere between black and white
is my dream to be a doctor.

395
00:23:27,724 --> 00:23:30,591
- I should get back to the ranch.
- Of course.

396
00:23:30,661 --> 00:23:32,652
Please tell my grandpa I said hello.

397
00:23:47,744 --> 00:23:49,678
Those sheets are rough.

398
00:23:49,746 --> 00:23:51,737
They're all I've got.

399
00:23:51,815 --> 00:23:54,010
<i>That cot is like sleeping on a board.</i>

400
00:23:54,084 --> 00:23:58,145
<i>And the draft in here practically</i>
<i>blows the blanket off my legs.</i>

401
00:23:58,221 --> 00:24:00,121
How long until I can leave?

402
00:24:00,190 --> 00:24:04,820
You can move to the hotel today,
Mrs. Stafford-Smith, if Belinda will stay with you.

403
00:24:04,895 --> 00:24:08,092
- Can you do that?
- But I thought I'd continue to work here with you.

404
00:24:08,165 --> 00:24:10,099
Mrs. Stafford-Smith needs a nurse.

405
00:24:10,167 --> 00:24:13,694
- I thought that's what you wanted to be.
- Actually I want to be a doctor.

406
00:24:13,770 --> 00:24:15,761
It's all settled then.

407
00:24:26,883 --> 00:24:28,817
<i>[Missie]</i>
<i>And "decision. '"</i>

408
00:24:28,885 --> 00:24:34,016
<i>D- E-C-l-S-l-O-N.</i>

409
00:24:34,091 --> 00:24:36,821
I think that's recess.
You're dismissed.

410
00:24:36,893 --> 00:24:38,827
[Chattering, Laughing]

411
00:24:38,895 --> 00:24:43,195
- You want me to keep an eye on them, Mrs. Tyler?
- Yes. Thank you, Sadie.

412
00:24:46,570 --> 00:24:49,334
- Is everything all right?
- You forgot your lunch today.

413
00:24:49,406 --> 00:24:54,070
Oh, you are so sweet to bring it.
I am starving. Thank you.

414
00:24:56,246 --> 00:25:00,239
Saw Charles Kent this morning.
He told me Sadie really enjoys working here.

415
00:25:00,317 --> 00:25:03,184
She is learning
more and more every day.

416
00:25:03,253 --> 00:25:07,212
She's already ahead of Caleb.
Now she can help him with his work.

417
00:25:07,290 --> 00:25:10,088
I know how much you want to help Sadie,
but Charles is a proud man.

418
00:25:10,160 --> 00:25:12,355
Pride is a man's downfall, Zach.

419
00:25:12,429 --> 00:25:16,763
He won't take it too well if he finds out
she's doing something behind his back.

420
00:25:16,833 --> 00:25:19,563
- I'll see you tonight.
- Bye.

421
00:25:25,108 --> 00:25:28,908
<i>Windsor, is this the best room</i>
<i>the hotel has to offer?</i>

422
00:25:28,979 --> 00:25:31,243
I'm afraid so, Madam.

423
00:25:31,314 --> 00:25:33,942
I suppose it's a step up
from the clinic.

424
00:25:34,017 --> 00:25:37,384
Still, these pillows are much too flat.
They'll never do.

425
00:25:37,454 --> 00:25:40,423
And surely they've got better linen.

426
00:25:40,490 --> 00:25:42,424
Oh!

427
00:25:42,492 --> 00:25:45,859
I'm mortified by these
inferior accommodations.

428
00:25:45,929 --> 00:25:51,299
But I'm afraid it's not possible to get
anything better in this uncivilized outpost.

429
00:25:51,368 --> 00:25:54,132
<i>[Knocking]</i>

430
00:25:54,204 --> 00:25:57,640
Oh, Miss Tyler, please come in.

431
00:25:57,707 --> 00:26:01,234
Madam, I'll just be down in the restaurant
to check on your tea.

432
00:26:01,311 --> 00:26:03,472
Wash the china yourself, Windsor.

433
00:26:03,547 --> 00:26:06,778
I don't trust these people
to have high standards of cleanliness.

434
00:26:06,850 --> 00:26:08,841
Yes, Madam.

435
00:26:11,121 --> 00:26:13,419
How are you feeling today,
Mrs. Stafford-Smith?

436
00:26:13,490 --> 00:26:15,754
How do you think I'm feeling...

437
00:26:15,826 --> 00:26:19,421
being forced to endure
these primitive conditions?

438
00:26:19,496 --> 00:26:21,589
You know,
we're not all uncivilized here.

439
00:26:21,665 --> 00:26:25,624
Really? Did I somehow miss
seeing the opera house?

440
00:26:25,702 --> 00:26:27,636
Or a good library?

441
00:26:27,704 --> 00:26:32,232
Or even a hat shop with
the latest fashions from Europe?

442
00:26:32,309 --> 00:26:35,176
No? I thought not.

443
00:26:35,245 --> 00:26:38,476
- Anderson Corner has other things to offer.
- Such as?

444
00:26:38,548 --> 00:26:41,949
Good people. And a church that
welcomes everybody, including strangers.

445
00:26:42,018 --> 00:26:45,249
And we take care of each other
in difficult times.

446
00:26:45,322 --> 00:26:48,314
You've never even been
outside this small town, have you?

447
00:26:48,391 --> 00:26:52,327
Actually I was born in New York.
I didn't come here until I was 14.

448
00:26:52,395 --> 00:26:55,228
So I do know a few things
about the world outside.

449
00:26:55,298 --> 00:26:57,357
But I much prefer Anderson Corner.

450
00:26:57,434 --> 00:26:59,629
You actually like it here.

451
00:26:59,703 --> 00:27:02,194
Compared to New York
it's heaven on earth.

452
00:27:02,272 --> 00:27:05,207
I'm going to miss it terribly
when I leave to study to be a doctor.

453
00:27:05,275 --> 00:27:08,802
Well, there's a surprising ambition
for a farm girl.

454
00:27:08,879 --> 00:27:12,280
- I believe it's what God called me to do.
- God? Ha!

455
00:27:12,349 --> 00:27:15,944
<i>Don't put your trust in God,</i>
<i>young woman.</i>

456
00:27:16,019 --> 00:27:18,783
He is unconcerned
with your ambitions.

457
00:27:18,855 --> 00:27:21,255
You don't mean that.

458
00:27:21,324 --> 00:27:25,488
The only thing you have
to rely on in this world is yourself.

459
00:27:25,562 --> 00:27:28,156
It must be awful lonely
believing in nothing but myself.

460
00:27:28,231 --> 00:27:31,928
When you've had a little experience
with the harsh realities of life...

461
00:27:32,002 --> 00:27:34,630
you'll abandon that naive faith.

462
00:27:34,704 --> 00:27:38,640
I've had a great deal
of experience of harsh reality.

463
00:27:38,708 --> 00:27:42,200
- Without my faith I expect I'd be much like you.
- How's that?

464
00:27:42,279 --> 00:27:44,543
<i>Very unhappy.

465
00:27:44,614 --> 00:27:46,411
Wha-

466
00:27:52,355 --> 00:27:54,550
Whoa. Whoa. Whoa.

467
00:27:59,396 --> 00:28:01,762
- Hello.
- Hi.

468
00:28:07,804 --> 00:28:10,967
Drew. I'm so glad
you could join us for supper.

469
00:28:11,041 --> 00:28:12,975
Belinda, I need some eggs, please.

470
00:28:13,043 --> 00:28:15,034
All right, Grandma.

471
00:28:16,813 --> 00:28:19,008
Everyone here works for their supper.

472
00:28:26,723 --> 00:28:29,556
- Might as well spit it out.
- What?

473
00:28:29,626 --> 00:28:32,288
Whatever it is you're stewing over.

474
00:28:32,362 --> 00:28:35,957
I apologize for being
so opinionated and outspoken.

475
00:28:36,032 --> 00:28:38,762
- You probably can't help it.
- Can you?

476
00:28:38,835 --> 00:28:41,030
Not to save my life.

477
00:28:41,104 --> 00:28:43,629
[Chuckles]
Truce?

478
00:28:43,707 --> 00:28:45,800
Truce.

479
00:28:45,875 --> 00:28:47,638
Truce.

480
00:28:57,654 --> 00:29:01,112
Remember, as I'm moving your arm you've got
to imagine you're doing it on your own. Okay?

481
00:29:01,191 --> 00:29:04,627
I saw you reading late
into the night last night.

482
00:29:04,694 --> 00:29:06,958
I'm so sorry.
Did the light keep you awake?

483
00:29:07,030 --> 00:29:08,930
My age keeps me awake.

484
00:29:08,999 --> 00:29:11,934
I'll turn out the light
earlier tonight.

485
00:29:12,002 --> 00:29:15,938
It must have been a very interesting book
to keep you awake at that hour.

486
00:29:16,006 --> 00:29:18,998
Oh, it is. It's called <i>The Laws of Life,</i>
and it's written by-

487
00:29:19,075 --> 00:29:20,838
By Elizabeth Blackwell.

488
00:29:20,910 --> 00:29:23,970
- You know of her?
- I heard her speak in Boston.

489
00:29:24,047 --> 00:29:25,981
<i>She's a very intelligent woman.</i>

490
00:29:26,049 --> 00:29:29,314
I can't imagine what it must be like
to hear her speak in person.

491
00:29:29,386 --> 00:29:31,445
You sound like you greatly admire her.

492
00:29:31,521 --> 00:29:34,922
She's done so much to pave the way
for women to become doctors.

493
00:29:34,991 --> 00:29:37,186
Ah. And that's
what you want to be.

494
00:29:37,260 --> 00:29:41,196
I'll be fortunate if I'm able
to train to be a nurse.

495
00:29:41,264 --> 00:29:44,233
The schooling for doctors
is terribly expensive.

496
00:29:51,841 --> 00:29:55,868
- You moved your arm.
- Your powers of observation are remarkable.

497
00:29:55,945 --> 00:29:58,140
This calls for a cup of tea.

498
00:29:58,214 --> 00:30:01,781
Now, imagine this is
your favorite Earl Grey.

499
00:30:01,915 --> 00:30:03,712
See if you can lift your arm
enough to take it.

500
00:30:03,783 --> 00:30:05,808
What, like a dog doing tricks?

501
00:30:05,885 --> 00:30:07,750
Like a woman who wants
her independence back.

502
00:30:07,820 --> 00:30:10,721
You are a very
impertinent young woman.

503
00:30:10,790 --> 00:30:12,724
And you are a very difficult patient.

504
00:30:12,792 --> 00:30:17,058
<i>If you apply your willfulness</i>
<i>to your therapy, you might get better.</i>

505
00:30:25,405 --> 00:30:28,033
[Sighs]

506
00:30:29,442 --> 00:30:31,342
We'll try again in the morning.

507
00:30:36,282 --> 00:30:38,750
<i>When you're done you can go.</i>

508
00:30:45,091 --> 00:30:48,390
Who is Charles Dickens?

509
00:30:48,461 --> 00:30:51,055
[Chuckles]
A very talented author.

510
00:30:51,130 --> 00:30:53,655
You can borrow the book if you like.

511
00:30:53,733 --> 00:30:56,566
Oh, no, thank you.
I'll see you tomorrow, Mrs. Tyler.

512
00:30:56,636 --> 00:30:58,433
All right.

513
00:31:08,982 --> 00:31:11,212
Hello, boys.
What can I do for you?

514
00:31:11,284 --> 00:31:14,447
- Mom needs some flour.
- All right. What kind?

515
00:31:15,555 --> 00:31:17,420
- She usually has wheat.
- Wheat's good.

516
00:31:17,490 --> 00:31:20,118
All right- Ow!

517
00:31:20,193 --> 00:31:23,890
- You okay, Mr. Browne?
- [Groans Loudly]

518
00:31:23,963 --> 00:31:27,626
- Mr. Browne!
- Dad! Mr. Browne is ill!

519
00:31:27,700 --> 00:31:29,827
<i>[Groaning Continues]</i>

520
00:31:31,571 --> 00:31:33,562
George?

521
00:31:34,974 --> 00:31:36,908
[Groaning Continues]

522
00:31:36,976 --> 00:31:38,910
George needs you
to take a look at him.

523
00:31:38,978 --> 00:31:41,412
He's got a pain.
He can't even stand up straight.

524
00:31:41,481 --> 00:31:44,416
Get him up on the table
and I'll look at him.

525
00:31:44,484 --> 00:31:46,918
[Groaning, Cries Out]

526
00:31:46,986 --> 00:31:48,920
Mm-hmm.

527
00:31:48,988 --> 00:31:52,788
All right, George.
You been vomiting, huh?

528
00:31:52,859 --> 00:31:54,850
- Yeah.
- <i>Mm-hmm.</i>

529
00:31:54,927 --> 00:31:57,794
Well, you don't have a fever.

530
00:31:57,864 --> 00:32:01,129
- You been into the, uh- the candy again?
- Well-

531
00:32:01,200 --> 00:32:02,827
- <i>Yeah, I thought so.</i>
- Aah!

532
00:32:02,902 --> 00:32:05,871
I got to get back to the office.
If you need anything, let me know, Doc.

533
00:32:05,938 --> 00:32:08,702
- All right. Thanks, Zach.
- Bye, Daddy.

534
00:32:09,575 --> 00:32:11,509
Uh...

535
00:32:11,577 --> 00:32:16,139
would you get my watch over there
on the desk, Belinda, and take his pulse.

536
00:32:17,517 --> 00:32:19,348
[Groans]

537
00:32:19,419 --> 00:32:21,944
Checking for rebound tenderness?

538
00:32:22,021 --> 00:32:25,047
Well, if you're so smart,
what am I doing now?

539
00:32:25,124 --> 00:32:27,615
- Using McBurney's point method
to diagnose what's wrong.
- Aah!

540
00:32:27,694 --> 00:32:30,060
- One twenty-five.
- And I suppose you have an opinion?

541
00:32:30,129 --> 00:32:33,656
I think he has acute appendicitis.
He probably needs surgery.

542
00:32:33,733 --> 00:32:35,667
If he has an appendicitis attack...

543
00:32:35,735 --> 00:32:38,203
it's not bad enough
to warrant surgery.

544
00:32:38,271 --> 00:32:40,671
- But if his appendix were to burst, Doctor-
- Burst?

545
00:32:40,740 --> 00:32:42,674
J-J-Just calm down, George.

546
00:32:42,742 --> 00:32:45,677
There's nothing to worry about now.

547
00:32:45,745 --> 00:32:48,270
- You can get up.
- All right.

548
00:32:48,347 --> 00:32:53,683
Look, if you get a fever
or if the pain gets considerably worse...

549
00:32:53,753 --> 00:32:57,280
you come and see me,
even if it's in the middle of the night.

550
00:32:57,356 --> 00:33:01,224
You take a teaspoon of this three times a day
till the pain goes away.

551
00:33:01,294 --> 00:33:04,058
And, George,
you stay out of that candy jar.

552
00:33:04,130 --> 00:33:07,099
- You're a grown man, not a five-year-old.
- Yes, sir.

553
00:33:07,166 --> 00:33:09,259
- All right.
- Much obliged.

554
00:33:11,771 --> 00:33:14,763
[Grumbling]

555
00:33:20,713 --> 00:33:22,908
Now listen here, young lady.

556
00:33:22,982 --> 00:33:27,112
A good doctor never performs
an unnecessary surgery.

557
00:33:27,186 --> 00:33:30,451
It's too risky,
unless the patient will die without it.

558
00:33:30,523 --> 00:33:32,457
But he had all the symptoms.

559
00:33:32,525 --> 00:33:34,857
If he had acute appendicitis...

560
00:33:34,927 --> 00:33:37,794
George would have been
right off this table from the pain.

561
00:33:37,864 --> 00:33:39,798
<i>Might even have passed out.</i>

562
00:33:39,866 --> 00:33:43,529
<i>Probably has nothing worse</i>
<i>than a simple stomachache.</i>

563
00:33:53,312 --> 00:33:55,712
Mama, what's this word?

564
00:33:59,819 --> 00:34:01,377
"Capture."

565
00:34:01,454 --> 00:34:03,115
And this one?

566
00:34:03,189 --> 00:34:04,918
Elephant.

567
00:34:04,991 --> 00:34:08,654
It says, " Then they went out...

568
00:34:08,728 --> 00:34:12,630
to capture the wild elephant."

569
00:34:15,134 --> 00:34:18,297
How do you know
what that says, Sadie?

570
00:34:20,006 --> 00:34:23,305
Mom is learning to read
at school with me, Pa. She's real good.

571
00:34:23,376 --> 00:34:25,970
<i>[Wood Hits Floor]</i>

572
00:34:27,146 --> 00:34:28,977
Charles.

573
00:34:41,394 --> 00:34:46,024
<i>You sure are a lucky man to have a wife</i>
<i>who cooks like Marty does.</i>

574
00:34:46,098 --> 00:34:48,032
I am blessed, that's for sure.

575
00:34:48,100 --> 00:34:52,196
I thank God every day that he saw fit
to put me and Marty together.

576
00:34:52,271 --> 00:34:55,206
- When did you first know you loved her?
- That's easy.

577
00:34:55,274 --> 00:34:58,209
<i>When I thought</i>
<i>I'd never see her again.</i>

578
00:34:58,277 --> 00:35:02,941
I felt a terrible emptiness inside of me.

579
00:35:03,015 --> 00:35:08,851
And I knew that if I didn't get her back,
nothing would ever fill that up again.

580
00:35:08,921 --> 00:35:10,855
That's a pretty clear sign.

581
00:35:10,923 --> 00:35:12,914
I thought so.

582
00:35:14,026 --> 00:35:15,960
What about you, though?

583
00:35:16,028 --> 00:35:19,293
Tell me about that life
you gotta get back to.

584
00:35:19,365 --> 00:35:21,629
- You got a young lady waiting for you?
- No.

585
00:35:21,701 --> 00:35:25,535
My father thought I should concentrate on
school before getting serious about anybody.

586
00:35:25,605 --> 00:35:27,732
- He may be right.
- He's always right.

587
00:35:27,807 --> 00:35:31,243
Sounds like a man
who's pretty sure of himself.

588
00:35:31,310 --> 00:35:34,746
If he's ever had a moment's doubt,
he hasn't admitted it.

589
00:35:34,814 --> 00:35:37,374
- Considers it a weakness, I'll bet.
- <i>Yeah.</i>

590
00:35:37,450 --> 00:35:41,682
He says if someone senses weakness in you,
that's when they go in for the kill.

591
00:35:41,754 --> 00:35:44,188
That's a pretty harsh way
to look at life.

592
00:35:44,257 --> 00:35:47,818
<i>But probably true.</i>
<i>In a legal battle, anyway.</i>

593
00:35:54,834 --> 00:35:57,428
Now, we can both go up on that roof...

594
00:35:57,503 --> 00:36:00,438
and you can find a way
to hurt yourself again...

595
00:36:00,506 --> 00:36:03,498
or you can take the wagon into town,
pick up those supplies we ordered.

596
00:36:03,576 --> 00:36:05,567
That's an easy choice, sir.

597
00:36:22,628 --> 00:36:24,562
Charles?

598
00:36:24,630 --> 00:36:26,427
Yeah?

599
00:36:26,499 --> 00:36:28,399
Heard what happened with your wife.

600
00:36:28,467 --> 00:36:31,300
You mean your wife.
She tricked me.

601
00:36:31,370 --> 00:36:33,304
I'm not apologizing for Missie.

602
00:36:33,372 --> 00:36:35,704
She was acting out of kindness,
and with the honest intent to help.

603
00:36:35,775 --> 00:36:38,573
I don't see how this has anything
to do with you, Sheriff...

604
00:36:38,644 --> 00:36:41,477
unless there's some new law
about reading that I don't know about.

605
00:36:41,547 --> 00:36:44,243
You know, there's no shame
in not being able to read.

606
00:36:44,317 --> 00:36:46,615
<i>The shame is from not even trying.</i>

607
00:36:47,553 --> 00:36:49,282
Good day.

608
00:36:59,398 --> 00:37:02,561
I know it hurts, but that's a good sign.
It means your nerves are kicking back in.

609
00:37:02,635 --> 00:37:05,229
- If you just try a little bit harder-
- I <i>am</i> trying!

610
00:37:05,304 --> 00:37:07,067
You're giving up too easily!

611
00:37:07,139 --> 00:37:10,267
Who do you think you are
to talk to me that way!

612
00:37:10,343 --> 00:37:15,440
<i>An ignorant, low-class girl in</i>
<i>a godforsaken town in the middle of nowhere.</i>

613
00:37:15,514 --> 00:37:19,644
I may not have a college education,
but I'm well-read and definitely not ignorant.

614
00:37:19,719 --> 00:37:23,678
As for class, I come from a good family that
could teach you what that word really means.

615
00:37:23,756 --> 00:37:26,748
- Get out of my sight.
- With pleasure.

616
00:37:36,535 --> 00:37:38,162
Windsor!

617
00:37:47,880 --> 00:37:52,146
Miss Belinda!
Miss Belinda, please! Wait up.

618
00:37:52,218 --> 00:37:55,551
Wait up, Miss Belinda.
Miss Belinda!

619
00:37:55,621 --> 00:37:59,022
I'm sorry, Mr. Windsor. I know you're used
to taking her abuse, but I'm not about to.

620
00:37:59,091 --> 00:38:02,288
Mrs. Stafford-Smith would never
mean to be abusive to you, Miss.

621
00:38:02,361 --> 00:38:06,161
I don't know what you call it back East, but here
we call it rude and unacceptable behavior.

622
00:38:06,232 --> 00:38:10,100
May I share something of
a personal matter with you, Miss Tyler?

623
00:38:10,169 --> 00:38:13,536
There's something
I'd like to show you.

624
00:38:13,606 --> 00:38:17,007
This is Benjamin and Lucy,
Mrs. Stafford-Smith's children.

625
00:38:17,076 --> 00:38:20,341
- I thought she didn't have any children.
- She doesn't now.

626
00:38:20,413 --> 00:38:21,971
Oh, I see.

627
00:38:22,048 --> 00:38:25,984
Mrs. Stafford-Smith became a widower
shortly after Lucy was born.

628
00:38:26,052 --> 00:38:28,850
Her children became everything
in her life, Miss.

629
00:38:28,921 --> 00:38:31,048
What happened to them?

630
00:38:31,123 --> 00:38:33,591
Lucy passed away when
she was five of scarlet fever.

631
00:38:33,659 --> 00:38:37,220
<i>Benjamin drowned just before</i>
<i>he was to graduate from Harvard.</i>

632
00:38:37,296 --> 00:38:39,161
How terrible.

633
00:38:39,231 --> 00:38:41,165
When Mrs. Stafford-Smith lost Lucy...

634
00:38:41,233 --> 00:38:44,361
the only thing that
kept her going was Benjamin.

635
00:38:44,437 --> 00:38:47,531
And when she lost him I was afraid she-

636
00:38:47,606 --> 00:38:49,540
I'm so sorry.

637
00:38:49,608 --> 00:38:53,169
That explains her anger and bitterness,
but that doesn't excuse her behavior.

638
00:38:53,245 --> 00:38:57,443
I just want you to understand that Mrs.
Stafford-Smith was not always the way she is.

639
00:38:57,516 --> 00:39:00,280
She was a kind and generous woman.

640
00:39:00,352 --> 00:39:04,083
Try to think of her the way she was,
before unbearable loss changed her.

641
00:39:06,158 --> 00:39:11,562
Try to see her with a forgiving heart
and not a judgmental mind.

642
00:39:28,514 --> 00:39:30,482
<i>[Knocking]</i>

643
00:39:30,549 --> 00:39:32,540
Come in.

644
00:39:35,621 --> 00:39:38,112
What are you doing back here?

645
00:39:39,725 --> 00:39:42,660
I want to apologize to you,
Mrs. Stafford-Smith.

646
00:39:42,728 --> 00:39:46,027
It was inexcusable for me
to speak to a patient like that...

647
00:39:46,098 --> 00:39:49,226
no matter how challenging you are.

648
00:39:49,301 --> 00:39:53,203
This submissive demeanor
is out of character for you.

649
00:39:53,272 --> 00:39:56,730
Does it have anything to do
with Windsor rushing out after you?

650
00:39:56,809 --> 00:40:00,336
He told me a little bit about your background,
but please do not be angry with him.

651
00:40:00,412 --> 00:40:03,142
He knows better than
to discuss my private life.

652
00:40:03,215 --> 00:40:05,410
He's devoted to you.

653
00:40:05,484 --> 00:40:08,112
<i>The only reason he told me</i>
<i>is because he believes you need me.</i>

654
00:40:08,187 --> 00:40:10,121
I don't need anyone to help me.

655
00:40:10,189 --> 00:40:12,657
We all need someone.

656
00:40:14,527 --> 00:40:17,655
I lost my mother, father
and baby sister.

657
00:40:17,730 --> 00:40:21,166
When I was nine my little brother Jacob and I
had to go live in an orphanage.

658
00:40:21,233 --> 00:40:24,168
- How did you get here?
- An orphan train.

659
00:40:24,236 --> 00:40:28,070
They go from town to town
giving kids to whoever want them.

660
00:40:28,140 --> 00:40:31,109
Sometimes they're good families
and sometimes they're not.

661
00:40:31,177 --> 00:40:34,772
If it wasn't for Missie and Zach,
me and Jacob would be separated forever.

662
00:40:34,847 --> 00:40:37,543
I'm sorry for you, Belinda.

663
00:40:37,616 --> 00:40:40,551
But now you know
why I turned from God.

664
00:40:40,619 --> 00:40:44,783
- No, I don't.
- How can you still have faith?

665
00:40:44,857 --> 00:40:46,791
I know we never really die.

666
00:40:46,859 --> 00:40:50,522
I'm connected to the people I love in life,
and I know we're still connected in death.

667
00:40:50,596 --> 00:40:55,397
A comforting thought if you
can believe in fairy tales, which I can't.

668
00:40:58,804 --> 00:41:01,136
That's enough for today.
You may go.

669
00:41:15,654 --> 00:41:17,645
Whoa.

670
00:41:27,633 --> 00:41:30,761
- Hi!
- Belinda.

671
00:41:30,836 --> 00:41:33,430
I was visiting my grandma
and she wanted me to bring lunch to y'all.

672
00:41:33,505 --> 00:41:37,134
<i>Well, your grandpa went into town to pick up</i>
<i>some lumber. He should be back soon.</i>

673
00:41:37,209 --> 00:41:39,507
I'll just leave this here then.

674
00:41:39,578 --> 00:41:43,514
Uh, wait. Why don't you stay
and visit a while.

675
00:41:43,582 --> 00:41:46,608
I can't. I should be getting
back to the clinic.

676
00:41:46,685 --> 00:41:51,384
Well, I was thinking that maybe, uh,
we could have lunch at the hotel sometime.

677
00:41:51,457 --> 00:41:54,858
- I'd like that.
- Tomorrow?

678
00:41:54,927 --> 00:41:57,862
Well...

679
00:41:57,930 --> 00:42:00,023
sure.

680
00:42:13,112 --> 00:42:16,275
<i>[Horse Whinnies]</i>

681
00:42:27,993 --> 00:42:30,223
- Evening, Charles.
- Evening, Mr. Davis.

682
00:42:30,296 --> 00:42:34,926
Drew Simpson is fixing up his uncle's place.
He could use some help.

683
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:38,436
He'll pay you a good wage, and I thought
you might be interested in the job.

684
00:42:38,504 --> 00:42:40,597
- Can I work around my hours at the store?
- You bet.

685
00:42:40,673 --> 00:42:43,164
All right then.
I'll be there right after lunch.

686
00:42:43,242 --> 00:42:45,574
- I'll see you then.
- All right.

687
00:42:45,644 --> 00:42:47,805
Mr. Davis.

688
00:42:47,880 --> 00:42:50,474
Thank you, sir.
I really appreciate the work.

689
00:42:50,549 --> 00:42:53,017
You're welcome, Charles.
You're welcome.

690
00:43:08,434 --> 00:43:10,425
Thank you.

691
00:43:11,503 --> 00:43:13,494
[Groans]

692
00:43:15,407 --> 00:43:18,934
I envy you your faith, Belinda,
but I can't share it.

693
00:43:19,011 --> 00:43:21,946
And even if I could,
it doesn't change the fact...

694
00:43:22,014 --> 00:43:24,949
that the only reason I didn't
let that stroke kill me...

695
00:43:25,017 --> 00:43:28,453
is my distant relatives
who are just waiting for me to die...

696
00:43:28,520 --> 00:43:30,988
so that they can inherit my fortune.

697
00:43:31,056 --> 00:43:35,720
I think the whole reason your stroke
didn't kill you is 'cause God has work for you.

698
00:43:35,794 --> 00:43:39,195
- You find a purpose by loving other people.
- And losing them.

699
00:43:39,264 --> 00:43:42,927
The fact that you grieve deeply
means you love deeply.

700
00:43:43,001 --> 00:43:46,801
There are so many people out there
who need what you have.

701
00:43:46,872 --> 00:43:49,602
- Who would that be?
- At the orphanage...

702
00:43:49,675 --> 00:43:54,305
there's hundreds of children without parents
or parents who simply give them away.

703
00:43:54,380 --> 00:43:57,008
Ah, so you're suggesting I give money.

704
00:43:57,082 --> 00:43:59,482
Not just money.
Yourself.

705
00:43:59,551 --> 00:44:02,884
<i>You have so much love to give</i>
<i>and they need love.</i>

706
00:44:07,092 --> 00:44:09,356
Aren't we supposed to be practicing?

707
00:44:11,330 --> 00:44:14,595
Reach for the teacup.

708
00:44:14,666 --> 00:44:16,531
One hand.

709
00:44:28,747 --> 00:44:30,977
[Gasps]

710
00:44:42,094 --> 00:44:44,619
Best cup of tea I ever had.

711
00:44:49,401 --> 00:44:52,234
- <i>[Charles] Hold it right there.</i>
- <i>Okay.</i>

712
00:44:54,473 --> 00:44:56,407
- That'll do it.
- [Chuckles]

713
00:44:56,475 --> 00:45:00,104
Thanks again, Charles. I'm not sure
what I would have done without you.

714
00:45:00,179 --> 00:45:02,477
You're more than welcome,
Mr. Simpson.

715
00:45:02,548 --> 00:45:04,482
Drew.

716
00:45:04,550 --> 00:45:06,541
All right. Drew.

717
00:45:08,053 --> 00:45:11,580
May I ask you a question?
About the law?

718
00:45:11,657 --> 00:45:13,591
Sure.

719
00:45:13,659 --> 00:45:15,593
It's about adoption.

720
00:45:15,661 --> 00:45:17,405
You and your wife
thinking about adopting a child?

721
00:45:17,405 --> 00:45:18,463
You and your wife
thinking about adopting a child?

722
00:45:18,540 --> 00:45:22,840
Well, not exactly.
Sadie was married before we met.

723
00:45:22,911 --> 00:45:26,642
And her first husband,
he was Caleb's pa.

724
00:45:26,714 --> 00:45:28,648
<i>But he was a real no-account.</i>

725
00:45:28,716 --> 00:45:32,117
He used to beat Sadie and Caleb both.

726
00:45:32,187 --> 00:45:34,212
- She divorce him?
- Yeah.

727
00:45:34,289 --> 00:45:39,124
He got in a bar fight and he hurt some fella
real bad, and they put him prison.

728
00:45:39,194 --> 00:45:43,221
Gave Sadie a chance to get away,
but he's fixing to get out soon.

729
00:45:43,298 --> 00:45:47,098
And I know he's gonna
come looking for Caleb.

730
00:45:47,168 --> 00:45:50,569
Now, if I can adopt him...

731
00:45:50,638 --> 00:45:53,664
does that make him my boy,
and then ain't nobody can take him away?

732
00:45:53,741 --> 00:45:56,767
That's right.

733
00:45:56,844 --> 00:46:00,302
Sadie's awful worried that
he won't give up his claim to Caleb.

734
00:46:00,381 --> 00:46:05,148
Well, under normal circumstances,
he'd have to agree to it.

735
00:46:05,220 --> 00:46:07,484
But because he's been in prison...

736
00:46:07,555 --> 00:46:10,615
there's no way the court
would favor him over you.

737
00:46:10,692 --> 00:46:14,184
- You sure about that?
- Well, I'll draw up the papers to petition the court.

738
00:46:14,262 --> 00:46:16,196
We'll see what the judge has to say.

739
00:46:16,264 --> 00:46:20,360
- Well, now, I can't pay you right now, but-
- You don't have to.

740
00:46:20,435 --> 00:46:25,566
- Well, I don't take charity.
- Consider it part of your wages for working here.

741
00:46:25,640 --> 00:46:28,700
Like a- a bonus
for doing a really good job.

742
00:46:28,776 --> 00:46:32,007
All right.

743
00:46:32,080 --> 00:46:36,073
- Thank you, Drew.
- It's my pleasure, Charles.

744
00:46:36,150 --> 00:46:38,516
I just passed the bar.

745
00:46:38,586 --> 00:46:43,751
- When I return home,
I'll join my father's practice.
- Does he practice criminal law?

746
00:46:43,825 --> 00:46:46,350
Nothing nearly so unsavory.

747
00:46:46,427 --> 00:46:50,090
No, he handles mostly contracts,
wills, trusts, that sort of thing.

748
00:46:50,164 --> 00:46:53,565
My father represents some
of the wealthiest people in New York.

749
00:46:53,635 --> 00:46:55,626
So you'll only be helping the rich people.

750
00:46:55,703 --> 00:46:59,696
- That's who our clients are.
- They don't have to be.
You could help the less fortunate.

751
00:46:59,774 --> 00:47:01,765
We work with people
who pay our fees.

752
00:47:01,843 --> 00:47:04,368
- Is that all you care about- money?
- <i>[Chuckles]</i>

753
00:47:04,445 --> 00:47:06,436
Don't be ridiculous.
That's not what I meant.

754
00:47:06,514 --> 00:47:09,540
It seems to me you don't
have a real passion for law.

755
00:47:09,617 --> 00:47:14,111
Well, the definition of law
is reason free from passion.

756
00:47:15,723 --> 00:47:17,953
Do you have time to take a walk?

757
00:47:18,026 --> 00:47:21,223
- I should be getting back to Mrs. Stafford-Smith.
- A short one?

758
00:47:33,341 --> 00:47:37,141
So, do you really want to be a lawyer,
or was it simply expected of you?

759
00:47:37,211 --> 00:47:40,772
It was always understood that I would
follow in my father's footsteps, yes.

760
00:47:40,848 --> 00:47:44,215
What does your mother think?
Or doesn't her opinion matter?

761
00:47:44,285 --> 00:47:47,550
Oh, her opinion would matter
a great deal if she were still alive.

762
00:47:47,622 --> 00:47:52,116
- She died when I was eight.
- Oh, I had no idea. I'm so sorry, Drew.

763
00:47:52,193 --> 00:47:54,127
You know,
for a long time after she died...

764
00:47:54,195 --> 00:47:56,857
I used to play this little game
every time I left the house.

765
00:47:56,931 --> 00:48:00,196
<i>I'd pretend that when I came home,</i>
<i>she'd be there...</i>

766
00:48:00,268 --> 00:48:02,930
hidin' somewhere waiting
for me to find her. [Chuckles]

767
00:48:03,004 --> 00:48:07,100
<i>Of course the only thing I ever found was</i>
<i>the latest governess my father had hired.</i>

768
00:48:07,175 --> 00:48:12,374
<i>He gave me every material advantage</i>
<i>I could ever hope for.</i>

769
00:48:12,447 --> 00:48:16,144
The only thing I ever wanted was my mother
to be there when I came home.

770
00:48:16,217 --> 00:48:19,653
- You're privileged to have both your parents.
- Actually, I was adopted.

771
00:48:19,721 --> 00:48:23,282
I would have never guessed
they're not really your family.

772
00:48:23,358 --> 00:48:26,384
- I mean, not that-
- [Laughs] It's all right.

773
00:48:26,461 --> 00:48:29,294
At first I didn't feel like
they were my family.

774
00:48:29,364 --> 00:48:33,095
They made me realize that loving someone
has nothing to do with being related...

775
00:48:33,167 --> 00:48:35,635
and everything to do with opening your heart
and letting someone in.

776
00:48:35,703 --> 00:48:38,467
I envy the relationship
you have with your family.

777
00:48:38,539 --> 00:48:41,736
- Why?
- You really love each other.

778
00:48:41,809 --> 00:48:44,607
I haven't felt that
since my mother died.

779
00:48:44,679 --> 00:48:47,842
That sense of security of knowing-

780
00:48:47,915 --> 00:48:50,975
Knowing that someone'll
always be there for you.

781
00:48:51,052 --> 00:48:54,180
You'll never be completely
on your own again.

782
00:48:54,255 --> 00:48:56,246
Yes.

783
00:48:57,625 --> 00:48:59,991
Exactly.

784
00:49:07,201 --> 00:49:09,431
You see?
[Chuckles]

785
00:49:09,504 --> 00:49:12,803
[Chuckles]
My, my, my...

786
00:49:12,874 --> 00:49:17,106
you have made remarkable progress,
Mrs. Stafford-Smith.

787
00:49:17,178 --> 00:49:19,874
I must say, I am very impressed.

788
00:49:19,947 --> 00:49:24,884
<i>To be truthful, I wasn't sure</i>
<i>you'd regain use of your arm.</i>

789
00:49:24,952 --> 00:49:29,082
Nor did I think so, but Belinda
was stubborn about my therapy.

790
00:49:29,157 --> 00:49:32,126
<i>She listened to me</i>
<i>grouse and complain...</i>

791
00:49:32,193 --> 00:49:34,627
but she never gave up on me.

792
00:49:34,695 --> 00:49:38,256
She's a remarkable young woman,
don't you think, Doctor?

793
00:49:38,332 --> 00:49:42,098
Yes.
Yes, she is, indeed.

794
00:49:42,170 --> 00:49:44,070
<i>Remarkable.</i>
<i>[Chuckles]</i>

795
00:49:44,138 --> 00:49:46,834
I know you must be anxious
to get back to Boston...

796
00:49:46,908 --> 00:49:50,241
and I think you can start
planning to go home now.

797
00:49:50,311 --> 00:49:53,940
Oh, thank you, Doctor.

798
00:49:55,983 --> 00:49:59,419
<i>So, what did you ride all the way out here</i>
<i>to ask your grandma?</i>

799
00:49:59,487 --> 00:50:03,150
It seems while I wasn't looking,
my life just got really complicated.

800
00:50:03,224 --> 00:50:06,455
This wouldn't have anything
to do with Drew Simpson, would it?

801
00:50:06,527 --> 00:50:09,052
I'm attracted to him and it's not fair.

802
00:50:09,130 --> 00:50:11,462
- To you or to him?
- <i>Both.</i>

803
00:50:11,532 --> 00:50:14,126
He's becoming a distraction.
I can't let that happen.

804
00:50:14,202 --> 00:50:17,968
<i>Everything seems to be getting</i>
<i>a lot harder all of a sudden.</i>

805
00:50:18,039 --> 00:50:21,406
Only a few years ago I knew
just how to get answers to my questions.

806
00:50:21,476 --> 00:50:24,138
You wish it was simple again
like when you were a child?

807
00:50:24,212 --> 00:50:27,613
You could say a heartfelt prayer to God
and then just listen for his guidance.

808
00:50:27,682 --> 00:50:29,912
Yes.

809
00:50:29,984 --> 00:50:32,919
Belinda, it's still that simple.

810
00:50:41,829 --> 00:50:43,763
Drew, you wanna take a break?

811
00:50:43,831 --> 00:50:47,665
What? Oh, no, no, no, I'm fine.
[Chuckles]

812
00:50:52,073 --> 00:50:55,167
- Somethin' weighin' on your mind?
- No, nothing.

813
00:50:57,011 --> 00:51:01,277
Have you ever had that experience
where you think a person is one way...

814
00:51:01,349 --> 00:51:03,214
and they turn out
to be something else entirely?

815
00:51:03,284 --> 00:51:05,718
I think we've all had that experience
at one time-

816
00:51:05,786 --> 00:51:08,687
I had Belinda all figured out.
Then I get thrown for a loop.

817
00:51:08,756 --> 00:51:14,023
- And that's bad?
- Well, it's... complicated.

818
00:51:14,095 --> 00:51:17,622
- She makes me think about things
I thought were all settled.
- Such as?

819
00:51:17,698 --> 00:51:19,893
Where I'm going to live,
what I'm going to do.

820
00:51:19,967 --> 00:51:22,993
Even whether or not my life
has any real meaning or purpose.

821
00:51:23,070 --> 00:51:26,471
Well, a woman can do that to a man.

822
00:51:26,541 --> 00:51:29,237
I know what I want to do with my life.

823
00:51:29,310 --> 00:51:31,972
I want to sell this place,
go back to New York...

824
00:51:32,046 --> 00:51:34,708
<i>go into my father's firm,</i>
<i>get married, and raise a family.</i>

825
00:51:34,782 --> 00:51:38,946
- Well, in that case, what is the problem?
- Belinda is the problem.

826
00:51:39,020 --> 00:51:41,784
I don't want to think about her.
I don't want to get involved with her.

827
00:51:41,856 --> 00:51:44,950
She's nothing like the kind of woman
I have planned for my future.

828
00:51:45,026 --> 00:51:48,359
<i>She wants a career...</i>
<i>in a man's field!</i>

829
00:51:48,429 --> 00:51:51,159
She's opinionated...

830
00:51:51,232 --> 00:51:53,757
outspoken, strong-willed...

831
00:51:54,869 --> 00:51:57,167
smart, kind.

832
00:51:57,238 --> 00:52:00,605
That doesn't sound like a problem, son.
That sounds like an opportunity.

833
00:52:05,146 --> 00:52:07,137
Whoa.

834
00:52:22,697 --> 00:52:25,530
Oh, it's not your hand again.

835
00:52:25,600 --> 00:52:28,034
It's my finger.
I think it's broken.

836
00:52:28,102 --> 00:52:32,266
[Exhales] There ought to be
a law against giving you a hammer, son.

837
00:52:34,141 --> 00:52:38,601
For your information, the first time
I hurt myself, it was on a wire.

838
00:52:38,679 --> 00:52:43,139
Maybe you should stick
to lawyering. Hmm.

839
00:52:46,020 --> 00:52:50,787
Belinda, why don't you, uh,
look at the boy's hand.

840
00:52:56,597 --> 00:52:58,565
Can you bend it?

841
00:53:00,234 --> 00:53:02,225
I guess I can.

842
00:53:04,205 --> 00:53:07,470
I think it's just a bruise.
I could splint it if it's broken.

843
00:53:07,541 --> 00:53:10,169
It might be quite cumbersome.

844
00:53:10,244 --> 00:53:13,042
Just leave it.

845
00:53:13,114 --> 00:53:16,550
Have lunch at the hotel
with me today.

846
00:53:16,617 --> 00:53:18,915
- I'm sorry. I can't.
- Tomorrow then?

847
00:53:18,986 --> 00:53:21,079
I have Mrs. Stafford-Smith to tend to.

848
00:53:23,024 --> 00:53:25,424
- Well, maybe we could find time-
- Do you want the splint?

849
00:53:25,493 --> 00:53:30,362
What? No. No splint.

850
00:53:30,431 --> 00:53:33,594
Then excuse me.
I have work to finish.

851
00:54:03,764 --> 00:54:05,561
Belinda, wait.

852
00:54:05,633 --> 00:54:08,193
I have to get home, Drew.
I have things to do.

853
00:54:08,269 --> 00:54:10,794
Why are you being like this?
What happened?

854
00:54:10,871 --> 00:54:13,066
- I don't know what you mean.
- Yes, you do.

855
00:54:13,140 --> 00:54:16,303
When the farm sells,
you'll be moving back to New York, right?

856
00:54:16,377 --> 00:54:18,504
Well, yes.

857
00:54:18,579 --> 00:54:21,980
And I'll be staying here.
So where does that leave us?

858
00:54:22,049 --> 00:54:26,952
<i>You'll go back to a life</i>
<i>I can barely imagine.</i>

859
00:54:27,021 --> 00:54:29,319
Meeting with rich clients
in a big office...

860
00:54:29,390 --> 00:54:31,915
<i>going to fancy balls with orchestras...</i>

861
00:54:31,992 --> 00:54:36,122
dancing with well-bred girls
in satin gowns.

862
00:54:36,197 --> 00:54:38,563
After a while,
you won't even remember me.

863
00:54:40,334 --> 00:54:43,201
Hand me that, please.

864
00:54:50,711 --> 00:54:53,202
- Come on, Drifter.
- [Neighs]

865
00:55:01,122 --> 00:55:04,683
<i>[Knocking]</i>

866
00:55:04,759 --> 00:55:07,819
Well, let's see who that is.

867
00:55:07,895 --> 00:55:11,922
- Hey, Charles.
- Evening, Sheriff. Awful sorry
to interrupt your family meal.

868
00:55:11,999 --> 00:55:14,024
Would you like to join us, Charles?

869
00:55:14,101 --> 00:55:19,129
Oh, no, thank you, ma'am. I just came
to drop this by. It's for Miss Belinda.

870
00:55:25,179 --> 00:55:28,148
It seems Drew hurt himself again.

871
00:55:28,215 --> 00:55:32,584
I better go check on him.
I'll be back as soon as I can, Mama.

872
00:55:33,687 --> 00:55:36,212
- Thank you, Charles.
- Sheriff.

873
00:55:36,290 --> 00:55:39,225
<i>[Hoofbeats Pounding]</i>

874
00:55:56,043 --> 00:55:58,034
Drew?

875
00:56:04,985 --> 00:56:08,250
What?

876
00:56:08,322 --> 00:56:11,416
- I believe this belonged to my aunt.
- ## [Music Box]

877
00:56:11,492 --> 00:56:14,984
Probably meant
a great deal to my uncle.

878
00:56:16,363 --> 00:56:18,923
[Sighs]
This isn't a fancy ballroom.

879
00:56:18,999 --> 00:56:21,092
There isn't an orchestra.

880
00:56:23,337 --> 00:56:26,329
<i>## [Continues]</i>

881
00:56:28,609 --> 00:56:30,634
But if I can have this dance...

882
00:56:30,711 --> 00:56:33,612
I promise you, Belinda,
that I will never forget it.

883
00:57:11,819 --> 00:57:14,413
You know this doesn't
change anything, Drew.

884
00:57:14,488 --> 00:57:18,584
- I think it changes everything.
- I should go in.

885
00:57:18,659 --> 00:57:20,524
<i>I'll see you tomorrow.</i>

886
00:57:21,662 --> 00:57:23,653
- I don't think-
- Tomorrow.

887
00:57:28,836 --> 00:57:30,770
[Man]
Hyah!

888
00:57:30,838 --> 00:57:34,797
<i>Dr. Jackson has given me the go-ahead</i>
<i>to travel home to Boston.</i>

889
00:57:34,875 --> 00:57:39,175
I'm very happy for you, Mrs. Stafford-Smith,
but I am gonna miss you.

890
00:57:39,246 --> 00:57:41,237
I'd like you to come with me, Belinda.

891
00:57:41,315 --> 00:57:44,079
If you're worried about
the travel, Mister-

892
00:57:44,151 --> 00:57:47,018
No, I'm not looking
for a traveling companion.

893
00:57:47,087 --> 00:57:49,521
I'd like you to come back
to Boston and live with me.

894
00:57:49,590 --> 00:57:53,117
Take me to that orphanage.
I'd like to meet those children.

895
00:57:53,193 --> 00:57:56,754
You don't need me to take you there.
I'll just get you the name of the orphanage.

896
00:57:56,830 --> 00:57:58,764
No.
Well, Belinda, there's more.

897
00:57:58,832 --> 00:58:02,199
I would like to pay your way
through college and medical school.

898
00:58:02,269 --> 00:58:06,729
<i>You shouldn't have to settle</i>
<i>for small dreams.</i>

899
00:58:06,807 --> 00:58:11,301
<i>Dare to go for the big ones!</i>
<i>You'll make a fine doctor, Belinda.</i>

900
00:58:11,378 --> 00:58:14,779
That's a much too generous offer,
Mrs. Stafford-Smith.

901
00:58:14,848 --> 00:58:17,578
<i>I'm afraid I can't accept it.</i>

902
00:58:17,651 --> 00:58:22,054
- Why on earth not?
- Because it would take me years
and years to pay you back.

903
00:58:22,122 --> 00:58:24,989
Well, it's not a loan, it's a gift.

904
00:58:25,059 --> 00:58:29,120
I'm a very wealthy woman.
I can afford to do this for you.

905
00:58:29,196 --> 00:58:34,463
I would like to think,
